a) O(n)

The worst case time complexity of the binary tree sort is O(n) because it requires you to compare every node to its left and right child, which takes a maximum of O(log n) comparisons, followed by the standard O(n) comparison to determine the order of the node. This is the same order of growth as the most basic comparison sort algorithm, which sorts the entire unsorted part of the list in one comparison.

Answer: c) preorder.

Explanation:

* First, we construct the binary search tree by selecting the left subtree from the root and then selecting the smallest element in the empty right subtree to make it the rightmost node as the parent of the left subtree.
* We perform a preorder traversal, which means we start at the root node and visit the left child, then the parent node, and finally the right child.
* This order is the same as sorting in ascending order.

On the other hand, inorder traversal visits the left child after the parent node and after the right child. Therefore, inorder traversal is not used for binary tree sort.

Postorder traversal is performed by first visiting all the nodes in the left subtree, then all the nodes in the right subtree, and finally all the nodes in the root node.

Level order traversal is performed by visiting each level of the tree in order, starting from the top level to the bottom level.
